pects of traditional masculinity, sexism, racism, and heterosexism, there are exceptions in these discourses. For instance, the most popular national host, Jim Rome, is against homophobia and racism in sport, which indicates that the medium may be a place for male sports fans to discuss gender, race, and sexuality in consequential ways. Nylund concludes that sports talk radio creates a male bonding community that has genuine moments of intimacy and connection, signifying the potential for new forms of masculinity to emerge, while simultaneously reproducing traditional forms of masculinity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMasculinityxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aMasculinityzUnited States. 0aMenxAttitudesxUnited States. 0aMenzUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aRadio and baseball. 0aRadio broadcasting of sportsxUnited States. 0aRadio broadcasting of sportszUnited States. 0aRadio talk showsxUnited States. 0aRadio talk showszUnited States. 4aCultural Studies : Popular Culture. 4aGender and Sexuality : Men's Studies. 4aSociology : Sociology. 4aSociology : Sports and Society. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Radio.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791479421423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791479421/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles